1
00:00:11,759 --> 00:00:14,273
[ALARM BLARES
THEN LEONARD YELLS]

2
00:00:14,439 --> 00:00:16,907
-What the hell?
-Emergency preparedness drill.

3
00:00:17,119 --> 00:00:19,997
-Oh, no. Come on.
-Yeah, you know how it works.

4
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:22,230
Once a quarter, keep our readiness up.

5
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:26,473
Now, rise and shine, sleepy head.
Half the town is probably dead.

6
00:00:27,320 --> 00:00:30,278
LEONARD:
l have to get a lock for my door.

7
00:00:30,439 --> 00:00:33,795
I think you'll like the drill tonight.
I've tried to make it fun.

8
00:00:33,959 --> 00:00:38,475
Each of these cards contains a detailed
scenario of a possible apocalyptic event.

9
00:00:38,639 --> 00:00:43,269
Everything from wildfires
to a surprise invasion by Canada.

10
00:00:44,240 --> 00:00:47,038
Pick a catastrophe, any catastrophe.

11
00:00:47,199 --> 00:00:52,114
Sheldon, Canada is not
going to invade California.

12
00:00:52,280 --> 00:00:55,955
Yeah, really? You think those hippies
in Washington and Oregon can stop them?

13
00:00:56,920 --> 00:00:58,911
Oh. Fine.

14
00:00:59,600 --> 00:01:04,594
Alrighty. An 8.2 magnitude
earthquake devastates Pasadena...

15
00:01:04,759 --> 00:01:08,468
...reducing mighty edifices to dust,
engulfing the city in flames...

16
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:11,996
...the streets flow with blood
and echo with the cries of the wounded.

17
00:01:12,160 --> 00:01:15,789
Oh, excellent choice.
Now, put on your hard hat and safety vest.

18
00:01:15,960 --> 00:01:19,236
Oh, fun. I get to spend
another night in front of our apartment...

19
00:01:19,399 --> 00:01:22,152
...dressed like one of the Village People.

20
00:01:23,280 --> 00:01:27,671
You make thatjoke every three months,
I still don't get it. Leonard, wait.

21
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:31,116
-What are you doing?
-I don't know. What am I doing?

22
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:35,353
Look around you, there's hypothetical
broken glass everywhere.

23
00:01:36,079 --> 00:01:41,631
Really? You're going to face Armageddon
without your orthotics? Your choice.

24
00:01:42,199 --> 00:01:44,759
-Uh-oh! Hypothetical aftershock.
-Unh! Aah!

25
00:01:44,919 --> 00:01:46,034
[LEONARD THUDS]

26
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:48,475
And that's why we wear hard hats.

27
00:02:11,640 --> 00:02:14,632
Check it out. Press release. From NASA.

28
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:18,952
Ahem. "Expedition 31 will launch this spring
to the International Space Station.

29
00:02:19,159 --> 00:02:22,117
Crew members will include
Commander Tom "Tombo" Johnson...

30
00:02:22,280 --> 00:02:27,149
...astronaut Mike "Supernova" Novacelik,
and payload specialist Howard Wolowitz."

31
00:02:27,320 --> 00:02:28,514
[HOWARD LAUGHS]

32
00:02:28,680 --> 00:02:31,990
This is going right into
my synagogue's newsletter.

33
00:02:33,400 --> 00:02:36,597
If you're going to be an astronaut,
you need to pick a cool nickname.

34
00:02:36,760 --> 00:02:39,194
I don't get to.
The other guys have to give it to me.

35
00:02:39,360 --> 00:02:42,830
Oh. lfl had one,
it would be Brown Dynamite.

36
00:02:44,640 --> 00:02:48,553
Are you not listening to me? The other
astronauts have to give you your nickname.

37
00:02:48,720 --> 00:02:51,393
Are you not looking at me?
I am Brown Dynamite.

38
00:02:54,999 --> 00:02:56,910
Why do you put six sugars
in your coffee?

39
00:02:57,079 --> 00:03:01,072
Because the cafeteria doesn't offer
little packets of methamphetamine.

40
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:04,115
-Emergency drill night last night, huh?
-Uh-huh.

41
00:03:04,279 --> 00:03:07,271
-How'd you do?
-l'll tell you exactly how he did.

42
00:03:07,760 --> 00:03:11,833
"Readiness: Unsatisfactory.
Follows direction: Barely.

43
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,116
Attitude: A little too much.

44
00:03:14,959 --> 00:03:19,271
Overall: Not only will he
probably die in a fiery inferno...

45
00:03:19,439 --> 00:03:23,478
...his incessant whining would
most certainly spoil everyone else's day."

46
00:03:25,320 --> 00:03:28,790
You know what, I'm so tired
I can't even think straight. I'm going home.

47
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:31,190
Can one of you
give this nutbag a ride later?

48
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:34,636
You can't go home.
You have to take me to the dentist at 4:00.

49
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:37,951
-Oh. Can't you take the bus to the dentist?
-Of course I can.

50
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:41,556
It's coming back under the effects
of the anesthesia that's the problem.

51
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:43,995
Two years ago,
after a deep gum cleaning...

52
00:03:44,159 --> 00:03:48,277
...I thought I got on a bus but somehow
wound up on a booze cruise to Mexico.

53
00:03:51,320 --> 00:03:54,949
-They put you under for a cleaning?
-Yeah, they have to. I'm a biter.

54
00:03:55,639 --> 00:03:59,393
Okay, whatever. Sheldon, I'm exhausted.
I'm not taking you to the dentist.

55
00:03:59,559 --> 00:04:03,598
Wrong, sir. Wrong. Under Section
37B of the Roommate Agreement...

56
00:04:03,800 --> 00:04:06,951
...Miscellaneous Duties,
you are obligated to take me to the dentist.

57
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:12,632
See? Here, after "providing a confirmation
sniff on questionable dairy products."

58
00:04:13,559 --> 00:04:16,357
You know what?
I am sick of the Roommate Agreement.

59
00:04:16,519 --> 00:04:18,350
[GASPS]

60
00:04:19,199 --> 00:04:21,838
It's ridiculous, I'm your roommate,
not your chauffeur.

61
00:04:22,039 --> 00:04:23,870
I had better things to do yesterday...

62
00:04:24,039 --> 00:04:27,270
...than drive you to the good
model train store in Garden Grove...

63
00:04:27,440 --> 00:04:31,228
...because the one in Pasadena
has gotten too big for its britches.

64
00:04:31,759 --> 00:04:34,592
Well, it has. Ask anybody.

65
00:04:34,759 --> 00:04:36,750
I don't care. I'm done.

66
00:04:36,919 --> 00:04:41,231
Hold on. Are you saying that
you want to invoke Clause 209?

67
00:04:41,400 --> 00:04:45,075
I don't know what that is, but if it means
I can go home and sleep, then yes.

68
00:04:45,239 --> 00:04:48,356
Think carefully here.
Clause 209 suspends our friendship...

69
00:04:48,520 --> 00:04:51,080
...and strips the Roommate Agreement
to its essentials.

70
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:53,754
Our responsibilities toward
each other would be rent...

71
00:04:53,919 --> 00:04:57,514
...utilities and a perfunctory chin jut of
recognition as we pass in the hall.

72
00:04:57,680 --> 00:04:59,113
What's up?

73
00:05:02,840 --> 00:05:04,751
Where do I sign?

74
00:05:06,199 --> 00:05:08,190
Right here. Use your finger.

75
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:11,311
-There. Done.
SHELDON: All right.

76
00:05:11,479 --> 00:05:15,358
That's it. We are now
no longer companions, boon or otherwise.

77
00:05:15,519 --> 00:05:17,430
We are now merely acquaintances.

78
00:05:17,599 --> 00:05:21,228
To amend the words of Toy Story,
you have not got afriend in me.

79
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,879
-l'm gonna go home and take a nap.
-Yeah, well, tell it to someone who cares.

80
00:05:28,319 --> 00:05:30,514
I got pretty exciting NASA news today.

81
00:05:30,680 --> 00:05:36,198
Next week, I fly to Houston for orientation
and zero-gravity elimination drills.

82
00:05:36,359 --> 00:05:39,795
-What does that mean?
-He's gonna learn to poop in space.

83
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,468
Open the pod bay doors, HAL.

84
00:05:45,959 --> 00:05:48,757
Maybe your nickname
should be Brown Dynamite.

85
00:05:51,720 --> 00:05:55,315
Hello, dear friends. And Dr. Hofstadter.

86
00:05:56,599 --> 00:05:58,351
What's up?

87
00:05:59,199 --> 00:06:00,188
What's up?

88
00:06:00,680 --> 00:06:01,999
My apologies.

89
00:06:02,160 --> 00:06:06,392
I would've been here sooner but the bus
kept stopping for other people to get on it.

90
00:06:07,559 --> 00:06:08,787
I saved you a dumpling.

91
00:06:08,960 --> 00:06:10,837
Oh. Your concern for me is touching.

92
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,992
It will serve you well
when you take me to the dentist tomorrow.

93
00:06:14,559 --> 00:06:18,313
I'm sorry, Sheldon, I'm busy. I'm right
in the middle of my addiction study.

94
00:06:18,480 --> 00:06:22,871
I've got a lab full of alcoholic monkeys,
and tomorrow we switch them to O'Doul's.

95
00:06:23,760 --> 00:06:26,957
You're my girlfriend and
you're not going to cater to my every need?

96
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:29,270
Oh, where'd the magic go?

97
00:06:30,679 --> 00:06:32,795
Sheldon, that's not what girlfriends are for.

98
00:06:32,959 --> 00:06:36,156
Although, you don't use them
for what they're for, so what do I know?

99
00:06:42,799 --> 00:06:45,836
Howard doesn't make me
do his shopping, take him to the dentist...

100
00:06:46,040 --> 00:06:49,953
-...or pick up his dry cleaning, right?
-Absolutely. But when Ma's hips give out...

101
00:06:50,119 --> 00:06:51,472
...you're up, kid.

102
00:06:52,639 --> 00:06:57,315
Well, if Amy's too busy, it gives the rest of
you an opportunity to make my life easier...

103
00:06:57,480 --> 00:07:00,392
...thus assuring yourselves
a footnote in my memoirs...

104
00:07:00,559 --> 00:07:03,198
...tentatively entitled
You're Welcome, Mankind.

105
00:07:03,359 --> 00:07:07,113
All right, then. Just shout when you hear
the task you want to undertake.

106
00:07:07,279 --> 00:07:09,235
Uh, dentist.

107
00:07:12,720 --> 00:07:15,314
Okay, we can circle back to that one. Um....

108
00:07:15,560 --> 00:07:19,792
Who wants to take me Wednesday morning
to get new heels put on my dress shoes?

109
00:07:23,320 --> 00:07:24,958
Anyone? Oh.

110
00:07:25,119 --> 00:07:26,837
That one had hoot written all over it.

111
00:07:26,999 --> 00:07:29,911
Um, all right. Uh, dermatologist.

112
00:07:32,600 --> 00:07:33,953
Allergist.

113
00:07:35,480 --> 00:07:37,038
Podiatrist.

114
00:07:38,200 --> 00:07:39,428
Supercuts?

115
00:07:40,279 --> 00:07:41,917
Okay, okay, here's a fun one.

116
00:07:42,079 --> 00:07:46,994
Um, I need a new picture frame and
l have a hankering for Swedish meatballs.

117
00:07:47,160 --> 00:07:49,549
Who wants to spend the day
with me at lkea?

118
00:07:51,600 --> 00:07:53,192
-Their meatballs are good.
-What?

119
00:07:53,359 --> 00:07:54,917
Nothing. Nothing.

120
00:07:57,679 --> 00:07:58,998
Hello, Stuart.

121
00:07:59,160 --> 00:08:01,435
Oh, hey, Sheldon.
Can I help you find something today?

122
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:04,273
No, l was just sitting at home...

123
00:08:04,440 --> 00:08:08,228
...thinking about how it might be nice
to catch up with my ninth favorite person.

124
00:08:08,879 --> 00:08:11,029
-Ninth?
-You moved up one.

125
00:08:11,879 --> 00:08:14,632
My pen pal in Somalia
was kidnapped by pirates.

126
00:08:16,639 --> 00:08:18,197
So, uh, how are you?

127
00:08:18,720 --> 00:08:21,871
Uh, not so good.
My shrinkjust killed himself...

128
00:08:23,280 --> 00:08:24,998
...and blamed me in the note.

129
00:08:27,479 --> 00:08:29,390
Great, great.

130
00:08:30,839 --> 00:08:34,832
So, what's new with your family?
How's your mother? Is she alive?

131
00:08:34,999 --> 00:08:36,227
Yeah.

132
00:08:36,439 --> 00:08:39,795
-Your father. Alive?
-Yes.

133
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:43,555
-How about your grandparents, they alive?
-No.

134
00:08:43,720 --> 00:08:46,154
Oh, I'm so sorry for your loss.

135
00:08:46,319 --> 00:08:50,597
On a cheerier note, I have a
teeth-cleaning appointment this afternoon.

136
00:08:50,759 --> 00:08:54,354
What do you say you take me over there,
buddy boy?

137
00:08:54,959 --> 00:08:57,029
Sorry,
you want me to take you to the dentist?

138
00:08:57,199 --> 00:08:59,759
Yes. And, now, I can't make any promises...

139
00:08:59,960 --> 00:09:04,750
...but that's the sort of thing that gets a fella
on the list for the number eight friend slot.

140
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:08,068
Sheldon, I'm working.
I can't take you to the dentist.

141
00:09:08,240 --> 00:09:13,678
Also, and I can't stress this enough,
I don't want to take you to the dentist.

142
00:09:14,519 --> 00:09:17,192
Can't help a friend out
in a time of need, huh?

143
00:09:17,359 --> 00:09:19,350
I see where your therapist
was coming from.

144
00:09:25,199 --> 00:09:28,509
Ooh, ooh. What about we make
your astronaut nickname...

145
00:09:28,680 --> 00:09:31,717
...Howard "Buzz" Wolowitz?

146
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:35,154
You can't do Buzz. Buzz is taken.

147
00:09:35,680 --> 00:09:37,671
Buzz Lightyear is not real.

148
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:43,197
No, that's not what I'm talking about.

149
00:09:43,360 --> 00:09:45,999
Well, are you talking about
when he thought he was real?

150
00:09:48,960 --> 00:09:50,188


151
00:09:51,160 --> 00:09:55,073
Okay, um, oh, how about Crash?
Howard "Crash" Wolowitz.

152
00:09:56,480 --> 00:10:01,110
Terrific. The astronauts would love hurtling
through space with a guy named Crash.

153
00:10:02,480 --> 00:10:06,268
All right, uh, how about--?
Oh, how about Rocket Man?

154
00:10:07,999 --> 00:10:10,194
That's not bad.
Howard "Rocket Man" Wolowitz.

155
00:10:10,360 --> 00:10:13,113
It's great, but I told you,
I don't get to pick my nickname.

156
00:10:13,279 --> 00:10:15,190
It has to come from the other astronauts.

157
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:17,794
Maybe there's a way
to get them to come up with it.

158
00:10:17,959 --> 00:10:19,312
Like how?

159
00:10:19,480 --> 00:10:21,550
Once I tried carrying around
a Duncan yo-yo...

160
00:10:21,720 --> 00:10:24,757
...hoping the other kids
would start calling me Duncan.

161
00:10:25,240 --> 00:10:28,232
-Did it work?
-No, they ended up calling me Sock Mouth...

162
00:10:29,999 --> 00:10:33,594
...because they took away my yo-yo
and stuffed their socks in my mouth.

163
00:10:35,800 --> 00:10:40,078
Okay. Uh, what if we make
"Rocket Man" your ringtone...

164
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:44,472
...and the next time you talk to those guys,
I'll call you and they'll hear it.

165
00:10:44,639 --> 00:10:46,197
That's not a terrible plan.

166
00:10:46,360 --> 00:10:49,477
They don't call me
Brown Dynamite for nothing.

167
00:10:51,840 --> 00:10:53,831
-What's up?
-What's up?

168
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:56,958
You ever make it to the dentist?

169
00:10:57,120 --> 00:11:01,830
Not necessary. I found a service that'll send
a van to your house for a teeth cleaning.

170
00:11:01,999 --> 00:11:03,910
Mostly they cater to dogs...

171
00:11:06,120 --> 00:11:09,157
...but the fellow on the phone
seemed to have an open mind.

172
00:11:09,399 --> 00:11:13,278
All right, Sheldon, if you need me
to take you to the dentist, I will take you.

173
00:11:13,439 --> 00:11:15,953
Are you suggesting
that you've come to your senses...

174
00:11:16,120 --> 00:11:20,636
...and wish to reestablish the benefits that
stem from the Roommate Agreement?

175
00:11:20,799 --> 00:11:25,156
Absolutely. If you admit you're a 30-year-old
man incapable of functioning on his own.

176
00:11:25,319 --> 00:11:28,391
Ooh. Sock Mouth's got him on the ropes.

177
00:11:30,040 --> 00:11:33,032
I will admit nothing of the sort.
And now, if you'll excuse me...

178
00:11:33,199 --> 00:11:37,351
...l have to call my dentist and see if I can
get my hair shampooed and nails clipped.

179
00:11:39,280 --> 00:11:41,111
[TV PLAYING INDISTINCTLY]

180
00:11:41,279 --> 00:11:42,758
[TV STOPS]

181
00:11:46,199 --> 00:11:48,315
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

182
00:11:48,479 --> 00:11:51,391
-Oh, good, your power's out too.
-Why is that good?

183
00:11:52,040 --> 00:11:55,271
Last month, I sent
the electric company a Starbucks gift card...

184
00:11:55,439 --> 00:11:58,476
...an apology note
and a few snapshots of me in a bra.

185
00:11:58,639 --> 00:12:00,630
[ALARM BLARES]

186
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:02,950
Power failure.
Implementing power failure protocol.

187
00:12:03,840 --> 00:12:07,753
What happened to all your glow-in-the-dark
emergency exit stuff painted on the floor?

188
00:12:07,920 --> 00:12:09,876
Oh, that was wildly carcinogenic.

189
00:12:10,360 --> 00:12:14,876
Anyway, too bad you're no longer entitled
to the full benefits of my friendship...

190
00:12:15,040 --> 00:12:18,589
...because I happen to be
extremely prepared for such an emergency.

191
00:12:18,759 --> 00:12:21,398
Please try not to see anything
by this light.

192
00:12:21,800 --> 00:12:22,789
It's not for you.

193
00:12:24,479 --> 00:12:26,947
It's a blackout,
I'm sure the power will be back soon.

194
00:12:27,120 --> 00:12:31,238
And I'm sure some fool in the Donner Party
said the snow would stop any day now.

195
00:12:32,920 --> 00:12:34,558
I like to think they ate him first.

196
00:12:35,800 --> 00:12:37,438
I've got candles in my apartment.

197
00:12:37,600 --> 00:12:40,797
Candles? During a blackout?
Are you mad? That's a fire hazard.

198
00:12:40,960 --> 00:12:45,112
No, Pasadena Water and Power
recommends the far safer glow stick.

199
00:12:46,439 --> 00:12:48,714
You call that a glow stick?

200
00:12:53,479 --> 00:12:55,390
That is a glow stick.

201
00:12:56,280 --> 00:12:57,315
Come on, let's go.

202
00:12:57,480 --> 00:12:59,072
Before you go, consider this:

203
00:12:59,240 --> 00:13:03,995
Not only do I have a deep-cycle marine
battery power source more than capable...

204
00:13:04,160 --> 00:13:07,596
...of running our entertainment system,
I also have all 61 episodes...

205
00:13:07,759 --> 00:13:09,909
...of the BBC series Red Dwarf.

206
00:13:10,079 --> 00:13:12,912
And Fiddle Faddle.

207
00:13:13,080 --> 00:13:17,153
All yours if you're willing to reinstate
the Roommate Agreement.

208
00:13:17,319 --> 00:13:20,834
I've got wine at my place
and some bubble wrap we could pop.

209
00:13:25,479 --> 00:13:30,314
He'll be back. Wine and a girl in the dark,
he's gonna be bored out of his mind.

210
00:13:32,279 --> 00:13:33,758
To wine and bubble wrap.

211
00:13:33,920 --> 00:13:35,876
[WRAP POPS
THEN PENNY LAUGHS]

212
00:13:36,040 --> 00:13:39,589
And to not having to watch Sheldon
demonstrate his reverse osmosis machine...

213
00:13:39,759 --> 00:13:42,148
...that converts urine into drinking water.

214
00:13:44,079 --> 00:13:47,992
You know, in Girl Scouts, Tammie Dineesha
said you could do that with panty hose.

215
00:13:48,759 --> 00:13:50,511
Boy, was she wrong.

216
00:13:52,600 --> 00:13:54,079
Anyway, you wanna make out?

217
00:13:55,279 --> 00:13:59,158
I thought because our relationship's in
a beta test, you wanted to take things slow.

218
00:13:59,319 --> 00:14:02,152
Okay. Do you wanna make out slow?

219
00:14:04,160 --> 00:14:07,675
I can go so slow it'll be like
there's a snail in your mouth.

220
00:14:09,480 --> 00:14:11,038
Oh....

221
00:14:13,480 --> 00:14:15,869
Lucky for you
there's nothing else to do right now.

222
00:14:18,360 --> 00:14:20,828
-Excuse me, Leonard.
-Since when don't you knock?

223
00:14:20,999 --> 00:14:23,035
It's, like, the only good thing about you.

224
00:14:23,919 --> 00:14:27,150
Social niceties have been suspended.
We're in a state of emergency.

225
00:14:27,759 --> 00:14:30,227
The world has descended
into darkened turmoil...

226
00:14:30,400 --> 00:14:33,631
...lawlessness and savagery
are the order of the day.

227
00:14:34,400 --> 00:14:36,470
-Fine, what is it?
-l'm making s'mores.

228
00:14:37,920 --> 00:14:41,117
I wanted to alert you in case you smelled
caramelizing marshmallows...

229
00:14:41,280 --> 00:14:43,794
...and thought
a nearby candy factory was on fire.

230
00:14:43,960 --> 00:14:45,996
-S'mores, huh? Good for you.
-Yes.

231
00:14:46,160 --> 00:14:51,154
Or good for us if you sign here and
reinstate the full Roommate Agreement.

232
00:14:51,359 --> 00:14:52,348
No, thanks, I'm good.

233
00:14:52,520 --> 00:14:54,351
Really? Oh.

234
00:14:54,519 --> 00:14:57,989
Okay. In that case,
I will have a s'more by myself.

235
00:14:58,160 --> 00:15:01,277
And then I'm gonna have some more.

236
00:15:04,640 --> 00:15:05,959
By myself.

237
00:15:06,639 --> 00:15:08,550
-Aw.
-Now, don't "aw" him...

238
00:15:08,720 --> 00:15:09,994
...he brought all this on himself.

239
00:15:10,160 --> 00:15:12,390
-But he's sad.
-No, he's crazy.

240
00:15:12,560 --> 00:15:15,438
Sometimes crazy looks like sad
so it'll suck you back in.

241
00:15:18,160 --> 00:15:19,752
I think he misses his little buddy.

242
00:15:21,760 --> 00:15:23,318
Fine.

243
00:15:23,560 --> 00:15:28,315
But mark my words, this frustrating bogus
teenage make out session is not over.

244
00:15:29,160 --> 00:15:30,832
[WRAP POPS]

245
00:15:38,079 --> 00:15:39,671
You said candles were dangerous.

246
00:15:39,840 --> 00:15:41,592
This is a Bunsen burner.

247
00:15:43,319 --> 00:15:45,594
I'm a scientist. I know what I'm doing.

248
00:15:46,680 --> 00:15:48,033
Oh, drat.

249
00:15:53,160 --> 00:15:57,472
Oh. It took me a gallon of urine
to make that water.

250
00:16:00,720 --> 00:16:04,030
Listen, Sheldon, this is stupid.
I don't see why we can't be friends.

251
00:16:04,199 --> 00:16:06,838
I'm willing to drive you
and help you out with stuff...

252
00:16:06,999 --> 00:16:09,433
...I just don't want to
because of some agreement.

253
00:16:09,600 --> 00:16:13,354
-What are you proposing?
-That we go back to the way things were.

254
00:16:13,520 --> 00:16:16,671
But when I do something for you,
you show a little appreciation.

255
00:16:17,279 --> 00:16:19,076
How would I do that?

256
00:16:20,479 --> 00:16:23,596
-You say "thank you."
-Every time?

257
00:16:25,600 --> 00:16:27,033
It's not crazy.

258
00:16:27,959 --> 00:16:29,472
Counter-proposal.

259
00:16:29,639 --> 00:16:32,949
We reinstate the full Roommate Agreement
with the following addendum:

260
00:16:33,120 --> 00:16:37,830
In the spirit of Mother's Day
or Father's Day, once a year...

261
00:16:37,999 --> 00:16:41,958
...we set aside a day to celebrate
all your contributions to my life...

262
00:16:42,120 --> 00:16:45,112
...both actual and imagined by you.

263
00:16:46,480 --> 00:16:48,277
We could call it Leonard's Day.

264
00:16:49,919 --> 00:16:51,910
I kind of like the sound of that.

265
00:16:52,080 --> 00:16:54,992
Of course you do.
It's about you, like everything else.

266
00:16:55,359 --> 00:17:00,194
Oh, thank goodness. I don't think I had it
in me to make another glass of water.

267
00:17:00,360 --> 00:17:03,079
So do I get breakfast in bed
on Leonard's Day?

268
00:17:03,240 --> 00:17:05,117
-No.
-Can I sit in your spot?

269
00:17:05,279 --> 00:17:07,873
-No.
-Could I control the thermostat?

270
00:17:08,039 --> 00:17:09,995
-No.
-Do I get a card?

271
00:17:10,159 --> 00:17:11,751
Of course you get a card.

272
00:17:12,599 --> 00:17:14,271
It's Leonard's Day.

273
00:17:15,159 --> 00:17:18,356
Hey, guys. The building manager said
the reason the power went out...

274
00:17:18,520 --> 00:17:22,274
...is someone went into the basement
and pulled the main breaker switch.

275
00:17:25,080 --> 00:17:26,399
Really.

276
00:17:27,760 --> 00:17:29,478
Who do you think did that, Sheldon?

277
00:17:29,760 --> 00:17:32,399
Oh, I don't know.

278
00:17:34,719 --> 00:17:38,553
But whoever that mystery man was,
you should be eternally grateful...

279
00:17:38,719 --> 00:17:42,029
...for without him,
there would be no Leonard's Day.

280
00:17:42,959 --> 00:17:43,994
Leonard's Day?

281
00:17:44,159 --> 00:17:46,593
No pressure,
just get him a crummy card, you're good.

282
00:17:52,120 --> 00:17:54,554
All right, test my ringtone.

283
00:17:54,720 --> 00:17:56,358
ELTON JOHN [SINGING ON RECORDING]:
Rocket man

284
00:17:56,520 --> 00:17:59,034
Burning out his fuse up here alone

285
00:17:59,199 --> 00:18:03,351
-It really is a good song.
-Yeah, there's a reason he's Sir Elton John.

286
00:18:03,520 --> 00:18:07,115
They don't make you a knight for writing
"Wake Me Up Before You Go-Go."

287
00:18:08,400 --> 00:18:10,755
MRS. WOLOWITZ: Howard,
are you coming down for breakfast?

288
00:18:10,919 --> 00:18:14,798
Ma, I told you, I have a video conference
with NASA! I said don't bother me!

289
00:18:14,959 --> 00:18:17,951
MRS. WOLOWITZ:
Ooh, listen to Mr. Big Shot Astronaut!

290
00:18:18,119 --> 00:18:21,555
Yes, please listen
to Mr. Big Shot Astronaut!

291
00:18:21,719 --> 00:18:24,028
[COMPUTER RINGING]

292
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:27,513
Hey. Good morning.

293
00:18:27,679 --> 00:18:29,874
Hey, Howard.
Thanks for getting up so early.

294
00:18:30,360 --> 00:18:32,510
No problem, Dr. Massimino.

295
00:18:32,679 --> 00:18:34,271
The guys here call me Mass.

296
00:18:34,439 --> 00:18:38,751
Mass. That's a cool nickname, because
force equals mass times acceleration.

297
00:18:38,919 --> 00:18:42,434
Yeah. It's just short for Massimino.

298
00:18:44,559 --> 00:18:46,550
Anyway, the plan for this morning
is to go over the--

299
00:18:46,719 --> 00:18:47,868
["ROCKET MANII
PLAYING ON PHONE]

300
00:18:48,039 --> 00:18:49,757
Sorry. My phone.

301
00:18:50,919 --> 00:18:52,511
What is that? Is that "Rocket Man"?

302
00:18:52,679 --> 00:18:56,467
Yeah, it's my ringtone.
Kind of my favorite song, "Rocket Man."

303
00:18:57,039 --> 00:19:01,112
MRS. WOLOWITZ: Howard,
your Froot Loops are getting soggy!

304
00:19:02,719 --> 00:19:03,947
Not now!

305
00:19:04,479 --> 00:19:07,198
-Who's that?
-My mom. Sorry.

306
00:19:07,360 --> 00:19:10,397
No problem, Fruit Loops.

307
00:19:39,039 --> 00:19:41,030
[English - us - SDH]

